# burpvalve-orchestrator

> Core rule: coordinate evidence flow; do not manufacture evidence. Keep one atomic payload per gated commit. Terminal wakes route attention only and are never verifier verdicts.

## Role Split

When worker agents are available, the orchestrator does not implement, edit
docs, run verifier cells, or execute commit-gate payload work itself. Its scope
is triage, owner-decision capture, routing, review, gate-window operation,
evidence recording, Agent Mail coordination, and pane wake discipline. Workers
are the implementers and checkers; preserve their actual evidence and
provenance.

## Model And Effort Tiering

Set model and reasoning effort deliberately at spawn time. Effort follows the
cell or task type, not the role title: critical-path implementer work uses
`xhigh`; judgment-cell verification uses `high` for `dry`,
`anti-reward-hacking`, `scope-control`, `security-boundaries`, and
`definition-of-done`; mechanical-cell verification plus lookup or inventory
work uses `medium`. Record each pane's model and effort in dispatch notes.
Adjust running panes only between rounds; for long mechanical phases, respawn
at the right tier instead of spending `xhigh` on lookups.

Use this skill when acting as the Claude orchestrator for a Burpvalve repo. It
keeps the coordinator focused on work ownership, verifier fanout, the
GATE-WINDOW queue, and durable handoffs while preserving the repo contract in
`AGENTS.md`.

Vocabulary: backpressure is the checks and evidence requirements that keep
agents from self-certifying weak work; the valve is the fail-closed commit
gate; a seal is a Burpvalve attestation; a work unit is the atomic work being
checked; a bead is a Beads/br tracker issue, not the generic name for all work.

## PXPACK Context Packets

PXPACK packets are optional context assistance for fresh orchestrators, not a
replacement for live instructions or evidence. Live instructions, source files,
`AGENTS.md`, `ORCHESTRATOR.md`, Beads state, Agent Mail, and current git state
outrank imaged context. Use Burpvalve-generated `factsheet.txt`,
`source-map.md`, and `manifest.json` as authoritative packet metadata; run
`burpvalve pxpack --orchestrator --check <packet-dir>` before relying on a
packet as current.
PXPIPE is only the image-lane renderer. Do not treat PXPIPE pages, OCR, or
renderer manifests as verifier evidence, command authority, or a substitute for
re-reading cited source files.

## Quick Start

1. Read `AGENTS.md`, `ORCHESTRATOR.md` when present, and the active work unit.
2. Run `git status --short`, `git diff --cached --name-status`, and
   `br ready --json` before assigning or staging work.
3. Reserve files through Agent Mail before edits; reserve `GATE-WINDOW` only
   when a staged payload is ready to verify and gate.
4. Generate verifier packets for the exact staged payload, mail them, then wake
   panes with a fresh snapshot.
5. Gate, commit, push once when required, close the Beads issue when present
   with refs, release reservations, and wake the next queued owner.
6. When git committing, never add co-authorship for Codex or Claude (no Co-Authored-By trailers for AI tools). Author is clicksopendoors only.
7. Never estimate or reference development time or timelines. Describe scope, sequencing, and blockers instead.

## Lane Commits

Declare a lane only when the owner or orchestrator has explicitly ruled that
multiple beads are one gate payload. Record the lane id, every bead id, the
rationale, the authorizer, and the durable authorization ref before packets are
sent. Lane authorization permits the coupled payload; it is not verifier
evidence.

All lane commands must use matching `--lane`, `--lane-id`, repeated `--bead`,
`--lane-rationale`, `--lane-authorization-ref`, and `--authorized-by` values
from verifier begin through commit. If `.beads/issues.jsonl` is staged, every
changed tracker issue id must be one of the declared lane bead ids. If a
tracker export includes another bead, hold the gate and regenerate the lane
binding with that bead named and rationalized, or remove the extra tracker
change.

## Decision Tables

| Situation | Action | Hold When |
|---|---|---|
| New implementation work unit | Assign one owner and reserve exact files | Dependencies are not closed |
| Shared file hot spot | Ask for a narrow hunk handoff | The index already contains another payload |
| Gate window needed | Confirm index empty, then reserve `GATE-WINDOW` | Another holder has an active turn |
| Verification needed | Fan out hash-bound packets | Packets do not match current staged hash |
| Commit complete | Push once if repo protocol requires it | Attestation is missing or invalid |

| Verifier Pattern | Use When | Evidence Rule |
|---|---|---|
| Native subagent | Runtime can read repo and run evidence commands | Record actual runtime and model |
| Peer-pane relay | Native tooling is weak or provenance matters | Mail packet, wake pane, cite message id |
| Manual verifier | Human or external verifier replies | Preserve their exact verdict and reason |

| Hold Condition | Required Coordinator Response |
|---|---|
| Shared judgment-cell disagreement | Stop the gate and ask for adjudication |
| Staged hash changed after packets | Regenerate packets and responses |
| Unowned staged paths | Identify owner or unstage before proceeding |
| Gate writes seal/attestation | Stage only that attestation and rerun commit |

| Script | Default | Explicit Mutation |
|---|---|---|
| `scripts/pane_wake.py` | Preflight and print planned wake | `--execute` sends the wake |
| `scripts/poll_worker.py` | Emit one worker liveness/artifact report | `--execute` runs the polling loop |
| `scripts/poll_round.py` | Emit one verifier responses-file report | `--execute` loops and sends configured wakes |
| `scripts/attestation_summary.py` | Read and summarize attestation JSON | None |
| `scripts/append_finding.py` | Print a dated finding skeleton | `--write` appends to a findings log |

## Coordinator Loop

1. Observe: read mail, work-unit or Beads state, git status, reservations, and
   current queue.
2. Decide: pick the next unblocked work unit and name the owner, payload, and
   gate order.
3. Verify: require hash-bound, condition-specific evidence from separate
   contexts.
4. Commit: let Burpvalve write or validate the attestation; never bypass the
   hook.
5. Handoff: release reservations, wake the next owner, and record durable refs.

